    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "`nvim_replace_termcodes()` escapes `K_SPECIAL` bytes in the string. This is usually not the expected behavior, as most other APIs and functions do not expected a string with `K_SPECIAL` bytes already escaped. For example, `nvim_input()` and the evaluation of `<expr>` mappings do `K_SPECIAL` escaping themselves. The only API that accepts a string with `K_SPECIAL` bytes escaped is `nvim_feedkeys()` with the third argument being `false`, and yet the third parameter of `nvim_feedkeys()` can be a bit hard to understand. Actually, the third parameter of `nvim_feedkeys()` was added so that one can pass a string produced by `nvim_replace_termcodes()` to it, but it has been poorly documented, so many people use it incorrectly.\n\nNow with Lua mappings, especially Lua `<expr>` mappings, there is an actual case where `nvim_replace_termcodes()` escaping `K_SPECIAL` bytes isn't expected. Consider the following mapping:\n```lua\nvim.keymap.set('i', 'a', function() return 'π' end, {expr = true})\n```\n\nOne would expect pressing `a` in Insert mode to produce `π` here, but it actually produces `πþX`.\n\nThere are several solutions here:\n1. Don't change any behavior. Just add a warning in the documentation of `vim.keymap.set()`.\n2. Change the behavior of `nvim_replace_termcodes()` so that it no longer escapes `K_SPECIAL` bytes.\n3. Add a new API that replaces keycodes without escaping `K_SPECIAL` bytes.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
